## Architecture Decisions

1. **Canvas timeline over DOM**: For smooth 60fps rendering with hundreds of subtitle blocks + playhead animation. DOM-based would struggle with large SRT files (1000+ cues).

2. **Zustand over Redux**: Minimal boilerplate, built-in immer middleware for immutable updates, easy undo middleware. Perfect for this scale.

3. **Framework-agnostic engine**: `parser/` and `engine/` have zero React imports — pure TypeScript. Testable in isolation. React components consume them via hooks.

4. **Time unit: milliseconds (integer)**: All internal timing in ms as integers. No floating point. Avoids IEEE 754 drift. Convert to/from SRT's `HH:MM:SS,mmm` at I/O boundaries only.

## Data Model

```typescript
interface SubtitleCue {
  id: string;           // UUID
  index: number;        // SRT index (1-based)
  startMs: number;      // Start time in ms
  endMs: number;        // End time in ms
  text: string;         // Can contain newlines
}

interface ProjectState {
  cues: SubtitleCue[];
  videoSrc: string | null;
  srtFileName: string | null;
  selectedCueIds: Set<string>;
  playheadMs: number;
  zoom: number;         // px per second
  scrollLeft: number;   // timeline scroll position
  durationMs: number;   // total timeline duration
}
```

## Milestones

1. **M1 Foundation**: Project scaffold, SRT parser/writer, core types
2. **M2 Engine**: Timeline engine (time ↔ pixel), snapping, collision
3. **M3 Core UI**: Video player, timeline canvas, subtitle blocks (render only)
4. **M4 Interaction**: Drag/resize blocks, editor panel, video sync, import/export
5. **M5 Polish**: Keyboard shortcuts, undo/redo, zoom/scroll, overlap warnings
6. **M6 Quality**: Unit tests, e2e tests, edge cases

## Risks & Mitigations

- **Risk**: Canvas drag/resize interaction is complex to implement from scratch
  **Mitigation**: Start with simple pointer event handling; iterate toward smooth UX

- **Risk**: Large SRT files (5000+ cues) may cause performance issues
  **Mitigation**: Virtualize timeline — only render visible blocks; use requestAnimationFrame

- **Risk**: Video codec compatibility across browsers
  **Mitigation**: Document supported formats; suggest H.264 MP4 for broad compatibility

## Done Criteria

- Can load a video + SRT and see subtitles on timeline
- Can drag/resize subtitle blocks with timeline updating in real time
- Can edit text/timing in side panel with immediate timeline reflection
- Can scrub/play video with subtitle preview synchronized
- Can export back to SRT and re-import without data loss (round-trip)
- Keyboard shortcuts work for nudge, split, merge, play/pause, delete
- Undo/redo works across all edit operations
- Unit tests pass for parser and engine
